22
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:43,500
NPR's Jennifer Ludden reporting.

23
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:48,240
Schools across the country are leaving  millions — perhaps billions — of federal  

24
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:53,340
dollars on the table. That's money that could  help tens of millions of children, including  

25
00:01:53,340 --> 00:01:58,860
kids with disabilities. Emily Harris reports  on the findings of a new NPR investigation:

26
00:01:58,860 --> 00:02:03,060
"The money comes from Medicaid, which  covers many health needs for students with  

27
00:02:03,060 --> 00:02:07,860
disabilities and students from low-income  families. Last year, schools got a total  

28
00:02:07,860 --> 00:02:13,980
of $6.6 billion. Medicaid officials say they  could be getting much more, but many schools  

29
00:02:13,980 --> 00:02:18,720
say the reimbursement process has been too  cumbersome to be worthwhile. Now, Medicaid  

30
00:02:18,720 --> 00:02:23,760
has simplified things. Deputy Administrator Dan  Tsai hopes this will get more money into schools:

31
00:02:23,760 --> 00:02:27,180
'You're talking about things on the  order of magnitude of billions.'

32
00:02:27,180 --> 00:02:31,380
"First, though, states have to update  their Medicaid policies. So far,  

33
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:34,260
at least 22 states have at  least partially done so.

34
00:02:34,260 --> 00:02:36,360
"For NPR News, I'm Emily Harris."

